introduction.md:
\begin{array}{ll}
1. \amp \text{a clear central question,}\\
2. \amp \text{at least two worked mathematical examples,}\\
3. \amp \text{a diagram, table, or carefully described picture,}\\
4. \amp \text{a connection to earlier chapters,}\\
5. \amp \text{a conclusion that says what changed in your understanding.}
\end{array}

subsection.p:
Chapter began with a strange question:
\text{Can we multiply vectors?}
In the plane, complex numbers answered yes. Multiplication by a+bi rotates and stretches. But in three dimensions, the answer was harder. Hamilton's quaternions gave one answer, and modern vector algebra later split that answer into the dot product and cross product.

Required mathematical examples. Include at least two of the following:

  \begin{array}{c|c}
  \text{Example} \amp \text{Purpose} \\ \hline
  (1+i)(1-i)=2 \amp \text{Complex multiplication and length}\\[1mm]
  ij=k,\quad ji=-k \amp \text{Noncommutativity}\\[1mm]
  (i+j)(i-j) \amp \text{Scalar and vector parts}\\[1mm]
  (1,0,0)\times(0,1,0)=(0,0,1) \amp \text{Cross product orientation}\\[1mm]
  \mathbf a\wedge\mathbf b \amp \text{Oriented area without choosing a normal vector}
  \end{array}

Your essay should argue both sides:

  \begin{array}{c|l}
  \text{Useful} \amp \text{The cross product gives quick normal vectors and area vectors.}\\[1mm]
  \text{Suspicious} \amp \text{It turns an oriented area into a vector using special features of } \mathbb R^3.
  \end{array}

Required examples. Include at least three examples:

  \begin{array}{c|c}
  \text{Example} \amp \text{Concept} \\ \hline
  \mathbf r_u\times\mathbf r_v \amp \text{Surface normal and area scale}\\[1mm]
  \mathbf r_v\times\mathbf r_u \amp \text{Orientation reversal}\\[1mm]
  \mathbf F\cdot(\mathbf r_u\times\mathbf r_v)\,du\,dv \amp \text{Classical flux}\\[1mm]
  \Phi_{\mathbf F}= F_1\,dy\wedge dz+F_2\,dz\wedge dx+F_3\,dx\wedge dy \amp \text{Forms flux}\\[1mm]
  \mathbf u\wedge\mathbf v \amp \text{Oriented area before choosing a normal}
  \end{array}

Your task. Write an essay explaining how the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus reappears as:

  \begin{array}{ll}
  1. \amp \text{The Fundamental Theorem for line integrals,}\\
  2. \amp \text{Green's theorem,}\\
  3. \amp \text{Stokes' theorem,}\\
  4. \amp \text{The divergence theorem,}\\
  5. \amp \text{The generalized Stokes theorem.}
  \end{array}

You do not need to prove every theorem. Your job is to explain the shared structure.

Required examples. Include at least three worked examples, chosen from different dimensions.

  \begin{array}{c|c}
  \text{Example} \amp \text{Boundary principle} \\ \hline
  \displaystyle \int_1^4 d(x^2+1) \amp \text{Endpoints}\\[2mm]
  \displaystyle \int_C df \amp \text{Potential difference}\\[2mm]
  \displaystyle \int_{\partial R}x\,dy \amp \text{Area from boundary}\\[2mm]
  \displaystyle \int_{\partial B} \left(x\,dy\wedge dz+y\,dz\wedge dx+z\,dx\wedge dy\right) \amp \text{Flux from divergence}\\[3mm]
  \displaystyle \int_{\partial S}\omega \amp \text{Circulation from surface curl}
  \end{array}

That gives the bookkeeping law
\boxed{\frac{d}{dt}\iiint_E \rho\,dV + \iint_{\partial E}\mathbf J\cdot\widehat{\mathbf n}\,dS = \iiint_E s\,dV.}
Here:

  \begin{array}{c|c}
  \rho \amp \text{Density stored inside the region}\\[1mm]
  \mathbf J \amp \text{Flux density crossing the boundary}\\[1mm]
  s \amp \text{Source rate per unit volume}
  \end{array}

p.md:
\begin{array}{c|l}
\text{Criterion} \amp \text{What a strong submission does} \\ \hline
\text{Thesis} \amp \text{States a clear mathematical question or claim.}\\[1mm]
\text{Examples} \amp \text{Uses concrete computations, not only general statements.}\\[1mm]
\text{Accuracy} \amp \text{Keeps definitions, signs, and notation correct.}\\[1mm]
\text{Connection} \amp \text{Links the topic to earlier chapters of the book.}\\[1mm]
\text{Clarity} \amp \text{Explains ideas in complete sentences, with diagrams or tables where helpful.}\\[1mm]
\text{Reflection} \amp \text{Ends by saying what the project reveals that a formula alone would hide.}
\end{array}
